      "writtenOn": "2026-07-21T10:33:08Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Thanks. Two parts:\n\nDocumentation. Board is now defined in schemas/platform/mctp.json and documented in docs/platform_configuration.md. In short it names the board inventory object this MCTP-over-USB device is associated with; consumers (dbus-sensors) use it to resolve that board\u0027s NvidiaMctpVdm configuration and associate the device\u0027s sensors with the correct board/chassis. And yes — the referenced board is a FOUND(...) precondition in the platform Probe (e.g. FOUND(\u0027Nvidia RTX PRO 6000 Blackwell 1\u0027)), so it does appear in the probe.\n\nPluggability / RTX5000. Today this config assumes an all-RTX6000 population. rtx6000_pro.json probes on BOARD_PRODUCT_NAME: \u0027RTXPRO6000Blackwell...\u0027, so an RTX5000 in a slot would not produce a ...Blackwell N board. The platform Probe AND\u0027s FOUND(\u0027...Blackwell 1\u0027..\u00278\u0027), so that one missing board makes the whole platform config fail to match and nothing is exposed — i.e. mixed / non-RTX6000 SKUs are not handled yet. Making the SMA→board association SKU-agnostic — binding it to the physical slot/location instead of a hard-coded board name, or Board as an array of supported entities (per Harshit\u0027s suggestion) — is a larger design change I\u0027d prefer to land as a follow-up rather than fold into this config commit. Happy to align on the preferred direction first.",
